<!doctype html>
<meta charset="utf8">
<link rel="stylesheet" href="./spec.css">
<link rel="stylesheet" href="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/highlight.js/8.4/styles/github.min.css">
<script src="./spec.js"></script>
<pre class="metadata">
title: Fused Multiply Add
stage: 0
contributors: Waldemar Horwat
</pre>

<emu-clause id="sec-fmamultiply" type="abstract operation">
  <h1>
    FMAMultiply (
      _x_: a Number,
      _y_: a Number,
    ): either a non-zero mathematical value, ~not-a-number~, ~positive-infinity~, ~negative-infinity~, ~positive-zero~, or ~negative-zero~
  </h1>
  <dl class="header">
    <dt>description</dt>
    <dd>It computes the exact mathematical product of _x_ and _y_.
    <p>The behaviour matches that of Number::multiply except that no rounding takes place and the result
    is either an exact non-zero mathematical value or an enum indicating a signed zero, a signed infinity, or NaN.</p>
    </dd>
  </dl>
  <emu-alg>
    1. If _x_ is *NaN* or _y_ is *NaN*, return ~not-a-number~.
    1. Let _sign_ be 1.
    1. If _x_ is *-0*<sub>𝔽</sub> or _x_ < *-0*<sub>𝔽</sub>, then
      1. Set _x_ to Number::unaryMinus(_x_).
      1. Set _sign_ to -_sign_.
    1. If _y_ is *-0*<sub>𝔽</sub> or _y_ < *-0*<sub>𝔽</sub>, then
      1. Set _y_ to Number::unaryMinus(_y_).
      1. Set _sign_ to -_sign_.
    1. Assert: _x_ and _y_ both have positive signs.
    1. If _x_ is *+∞*<sub>𝔽</sub> or _y_ is *+∞*<sub>𝔽</sub>, then
      1. If _x_ is *+0*<sub>𝔽</sub> or _y_ is *+0*<sub>𝔽</sub>, return ~not-a-number~.
      1. If _sign_ is -1, return ~negative-infinity~.
      1. Return ~positive-infinity~.
    1. If _x_ is *+0*<sub>𝔽</sub> or _y_ is *+0*<sub>𝔽</sub>, then
      1. If _sign_ is -1, return ~negative-zero~.
      1. Return ~positive-zero~.
    1. Assert: _x_ and _y_ are both non-zero and finite.
    1. Return _sign_ × ℝ(_x_) × ℝ(_y_).
  </emu-alg>
</emu-clause>

<emu-clause id="sec-math.fma" type="built-in function">
  <h1>Math.fma ( _x_, _y_, _z_ )</h1>
  <p>This function performs fused multiply-add according to the rules of IEEE 754-2019 binary double-precision arithmetic, computing (_x_ × _y_) + _z_ as a single operation with no intermediate rounding of the product.</p>
  <p>It performs the following steps when called:</p>
  <emu-alg>
    1. Let _nx_ be ? ToNumber(_x_).
    1. Let _ny_ be ? ToNumber(_y_).
    1. Let _nz_ be ? ToNumber(_z_).
    1. Let _product_ be FMAMultiply(_nx_, _ny_).
    1. If _product_ is ~not-a-number~ or _nz_ is *NaN*, return *NaN*.
    1. If _product_ is ~positive-infinity~, then
      1. If _nz_ is *-∞*<sub>𝔽</sub>, return *NaN*.
      1. Return *+∞*<sub>𝔽</sub>.
    1. If _product_ is ~negative-infinity~, then
      1. If _nz_ is *+∞*<sub>𝔽</sub>, return *NaN*.
      1. Return *-∞*<sub>𝔽</sub>.
    1. If _nz_ is either *+∞*<sub>𝔽</sub> or *-∞*<sub>𝔽</sub>, return _nz_.
    1. If _product_ is ~negative-zero~, return _nz_.
    1. If _product_ is ~positive-zero~, set _product_ to 0.
    1. Assert: _product_ and _nz_ are both finite.
    1. Return 𝔽(_product_ + ℝ(_nz_)).
  </emu-alg>
  <emu-note>
    <p>The single call to 𝔽 in the final step performs exactly one rounding of the infinite-precision product and sum.</p>
  </emu-note>
</emu-clause>
